    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-07-02T17:49:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-07-02T17:49:00-05:00" n="633"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">974.5301/7–253: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 633<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Egypt</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d633fn1">Repeated to London and Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-07-02T18:49:00-04:00"
                            >July 2, 1953—6:49 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9. In view protraction Anglo-Egyptian negotiations and renewed British and French
                    representations, US agreed participate tripartite exchange views re freedom
                    transit Suez Canal. Talks to be exploratory, on expert level, and to start mid
                    July after visit British and French Foreign Office representatives. We
                    delivering note re decision July 3 and stressing need secrecy. Will orally
                    request British and French not to raise this matter at high-level talks.
                    Discussions to cover points listed para 12 note quoted Dept A–246 Feb 3 to
                    Cairo.</p>
                <p>French Embassy June 29 suggested U.S.-French representations to Egypt at this
                    time stressing importance freedom transit and hope Egypt would observe this
                    principle, regardless future measures taken against British. We declining
                    proposal stating such approach uncalled for this juncture and would prejudice
                    chances Anglo-Egyptian settlement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
